death of an animal within the embryonic period prior to organogenesis (Mus: prior to E14)

definition.value: Note that a term with the former name embryonic lethality exists as MP:0002080. In many species, the terms prenatal lethality and embryonic lethality are used interchangeably. However, this is not technically correct and we have modified this ontology to define the prenatal period to include the embryonic stages distinctly from the fetal stages. The names embryonic lethality and embryonic death have been retained as a narrow synonyms for the prenatal lethality term to aid in searching for those species that may use these terms as synonyms.

definition.value: This term is used in conjunction with other lethality terms when the lethality is only partially expressed. For example, use this term when some individuals of a defined population die as embryos, neonates or by weaning, with some percentage of individuals surviving the lethal phase and achieving a normal life span.

definition.value: Ventricular pressure waveforms can be measured in the beating heart by catheterization or estimated using imaging techniques (e.g., Doppler echocardiography). The information is useful in evaluating the function of the myocardium, cardiac valves and pericardium, particularly with simultaneous measurement of other (e.g., aortic or atrial) pressures.

definition.value: Do not use for the initial specification of lymphatic vessels in early development; use for the remodeling of pre-existing lymphatic vessels. This term is similar to angiogenesis for blood vessel remodeling.
